Five truths about terrorism
São Paulo – US policy is held hostage by terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one American in six, or approximately 16% of the population, now ranked terrorism as the top issue facing the country – an increase of 3% in a month.
For the past ten years, no Americans had been as concerned about terrorism as they were at this point, although their numbers are still far below the 46% recorded immediately after the September 11, 2001 attacks.
The consequences of this evolution in public opinion were particularly evident during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
Donald Trump's candidacy, which features particularly fiery (and possibly incendiary) anti-Muslim rhetoric, has undoubtedly benefited from this.
Some politicians authorize themselves to speak of the war against terrorism as the "Third World War."
The terrorism problem was highlighted by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But whose presidential election candidates, just like certain media outlets, adherents to the old maxim "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated the proportions.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – as others do – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a sort of theater.
The terrorists are more concerned with grabbing attention and dominating political news than with the number of their victims themselves.
ISIL takes great care with its staging.
The barbaric decapitations broadcast on social networks are meant to destabilize and scandalize—thereby monopolizing attention.
To exaggerate their consequences and make big headlines with each terrorist action is to play the terrorists' game.
Terrorism is not the greatest threat facing the populations of developed countries.
Terrorism kills much less than car accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
You are more likely to be struck by lightning than killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen will be killed by a terrorist is, according to experts, one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (one in 950,000), from an accident involving household equipment (one in 1.5 million), hit by a deer or elk crossing the road (one in 2 million), or in a commercial airplane crash (one in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while texting behind the wheel or chatting on their cellphone.
It is several hundred times the number who die from terrorism.
Islamic radical terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings on university or school campuses.
Terrorism is not World War III.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a surge of terrorism.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed several heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Faction, emerging from the "autonomous" left, hijacked aircraft outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon cloaked in religious garb.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identity has been destroyed by globalization, seeking meaning in the imaginary and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of ISIL limits its appeal.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
ISIL will ultimately be defeated, just as the transnational terrorism that preceded it has been.
Terrorism is like jujitsu.
The weaker of the two opponents uses the strength of the stronger to defeat them.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have managed to overthrow one.
But if they manage to shock and provoke citizens of a state enough to push them to futile actions, they can hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda succeeded in drawing Americans to Afghanistan.
ISIL emerged from the ruins of the Iraq invasion led by the United States, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, it takes smart power.
Smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the army and police with the influence power (soft power) of attraction and persuasion.
The influence power is also necessary if we want to vaccinate those on the periphery and prevent the irreducible elements from recruiting them.
That is why the attention given to the narrative of events and the way US actions are commented on social media is just as important and necessary as precision aerial strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
Reason why the anti-Islam stance of some current presidential election candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious and deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important element of our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Do not fill the theater where the actions of thugs and criminals are carried out.
If we leave them the grand stage of our public discourse, we will diminish the quality of our civic life and expose our priorities.
Our force would then be used against us.
